    Larry Cohen - Date of publish: 7/15/2014 - Level: Intermediate    
|CP|1|fp||AT|^*Hlarryco.com/BridgeArticles/ArticleDetails.aspx?articleID=25^*N|CP||AT|}
^-|cs||fp||va|4|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|We've spent many months to get to the 2-level. Sort of. We did have a discussion of general approach and strong 2@C openings. Now, we have reached one of my favorite sections of the convention card. There are so many Bubbemeises ("old wives tales") when it comes to weak twos. Let's start with the easy stuff:|
hb|i|wb|b|ip|80|bm|http://ebooksbridge.com/www/ebb/images/manufacturers/cohen2RL.jpg|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


ht|i|at|^i@2In the first 30-40 years of contract bridge, all two-level openings were strong and natural. Then, sanity prevailed. Now, 2@C (artificial) is used for all (rarely-dealt) strong hands, freeing up 2@D, 2@H, 2@S for more practical use. Today, only dinosaurs use strong 2-bids (although ACOL and other systems where 2@D, 2@H and 2@S have special meanings are prevalent in certain areas of the world).|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


AT|

What should a weak two-bid show?|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|^*B Typically a 6-card suit and about 5-11 HCP^*N. Within that definition there is lots of room.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT| I wouldn't open 2@S with this hand:|
HT|p|at|^j|ih|pSK Q J T 9 8HDA 4 3 2C6 5 2|
ht|v|at|^j@2This hand is way too good'it is a 1@S opening.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


NT||
%%
qx||cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|Meanwhile, I'd gladly open 2@S with this hand:|
HT|c|at|^b|ih|pSK J T 9 8 6H4DT 8 7 4C3 2|HT|g|AT|^k@2Even though it is out of the HCP range.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


ht|i|at|^B@2At one point (in the mid-1980's) the ACBL had the "5-and-5 rule" (some people called it the "Marty Bergen rule"). You had to have at least a 5-card suit and 5 HCP for a weak two-bid. That rule lasted only a year or so. Now, "^*Banything goes.^*N"|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT|

There is lots of room for judgment. Vulnerability and position are crucial. If you are vulnerable, try to have a good suit and to be at the upper end of the HCP range. If you are in second seat (a bad position to preempt because the contract could easily belong to your side), be very sound. In all situations, be aware of suit quality. I don't think it is a good idea to preempt with a suit of ^*Bjack-empty-sixth^*N.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


AT|

