^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|I'll leave you this month with one more question: "What about using 2@D as Multi or Flannery or for other purposes?" If you want to, go ahead and enjoy. Personally, I find a weak 2@D to be quite effective (and easy on my memory). |
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


AT|

However, in most parts of the world outside of America, 2@D to show a weak-two in either major is quite popular. Try such a bid at your local duplicate (if it is allowed there) in the U.S. and you're likely to get some disgruntled opponents.|
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|I think suit quality is vastly overrated. Although I would open a weak 2 with some suits that Cohen might feel are too weak, in general we are in agreement. Having said that, I think Example E is a clear weak-2 opener even if Cohen does not. With Example H, although I would open a weak 2 with that hand in all seats, opening a weak 2 in 1st and 3rd seats but not in 2nd seat is a reasonable compromise.

The reason I push opening a weak 2 with any suit is because many students look for excuses not to open a weak 2. I think this is the opposite of what your mind set should be. Your mind set should be that you want to open a weak 2 any time you hold 5-10 points and a 6-card suit and you should be very reluctant to pass. |
PG| ***** 44 ***** |


AT|

